# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1871-chicago-white-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Ten of the twelve professional clubs from 1869 remained in that field for 1870, all except Keystone of Philadelphia and Irvington, New Jersey, from Greater New York.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] The five newcomers were Union of Morrisania, now in New York City; Tri-Mountain of Boston; Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio; Forest City of Rockford, Illinois; and the Chicago White Stockings, the only brand new club.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Union was a founding member from the 1857 convention and Forest City had been one of the strongest amateurs remaining in 1869.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] The records of the teams in professional matches, ranked by wins (see table), reveal three groups of five with sharp outlines.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] A big group of thirteen and a little of group of two are equally clear, considering the numbers of defeats, pro matches, and all matches (not shown), and are supported by the subsequent history.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] The two more ambitious newcomers played only a few pro matches and never returned to the professional field.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Mighty Cincinnati and venerable Union also shut down after this season.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] All the others joined the new professional association established that winter (NAPBBP), seven as founding members and four in 1872 or 1873.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] The Mutuals, Athletics, and Chicago White Stockings survived to found the National League in 1876.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Four amateur teams defeated professionals more than once and two of them demonstrated that they were as strong as middling pros.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Harvard college fielded its strongest team, which toured nationally in the summer and won 6 of 16 against professional teams all season.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Star of Brooklyn, featuring Hall of Fame pitcher Candy Cummings, won 6 of 13 against pros.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Pastime of Baltimore won 4 of 24 including 1 of 4 with the Troy Haymakers, 1 of 2 with Olympic, and 2 of 5 with Maryland.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] The Pastimes lost badly to Harvard and won one of three close matches with the Stars.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey won 2 of 8, both at the expense of venerable Eckford; the Resolutes remained in operation until a failed venture into the professional field in 1873.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek lists Lowell of Boston and the Keystone of Philadelphia (pro in 1869) among the major teams.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] They did not defeat any professionals but showed strength comparable to Pastime, Resolute, and the weaker pros.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Considering the professionals in three groups of five ranked by wins in pro matches (see table), the stronger pros won 37 of 41 against the six amateur teams covered here; the middling pros won 13 of 18; the weaker pros won 6 of 15.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Here are the records of those amateurs against the pros.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] One of the elite professional teams, the Athletics of Philadelphia won eight matches with Harvard, Lowell, Keystone, and Pastime, with 20 to 34 runs scored and 11- to 22-run margins.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Three amateur clubs of 1870 would later enter the all-professional National Association for one season each: Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana in 1871; Mansfield of Middletown, Connecticut in 1872; Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey in 1873.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] Harvard continued to field strong amateur teams, but amateurs would not again hold their own with middling pros.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1870-in-baseball] The Stars won a championship in 1871 under the new all-amateur Association (NAABBP), before Candy Cummings joined the pros in 1872.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The 1871 season was the first season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise, now known as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] They were formed in 1871 by Boston businessman and Ashburnham native Ivers Whitney Adams.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The team was composed of former players of the defunct Cincinnati Red Stockings franchise, who were brought to Boston and kept the name with them.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Led and managed by baseball pioneer Harry Wright, the new Boston team would join the newly formed National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1871 season and finish the year in third place with a record of 20–10.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 31 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 19 wins.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Cal McVey finished second in the league batting race with a .431 average.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] From this team, Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] The Cleveland Forest Citys played their first season in 1871 as a charter member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] They finished eighth in the league with a record of 10–19.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Pitcher Al Pratt led the NA in strikeouts, with 34.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] The honor of playing the first game of the newly organized National Association of Professional Baseball Players was decided by coin flip.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Bobby Mathews, 5 ft 5 in (1.65 m), 140 lbs, and 20 years old, hurled a 2-0 shutout for the Kekiongas.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Deacon White, catcher for the Cleveland Forest Citys got 3 hits in 4 at-bats; the other Cleveland players only shared 2 hits among them.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Deacon White scored the first hit, the first extra-base hit (a double) and was the first to hit into a double-play.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] The game was rained out in the top of the 9th inning.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Bobby Mathews, who went on to play five seasons each in the National Association, National League, and American Association, is the only player ever to pitch 100 games or to win at least 50 in three different major leagues.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] He is credited with inventing the spitball and the out-curve.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-cleveland-forest-citys-season] Deacon White was another historic player, ending his 22-year career as playing owner of Buffalo's Brotherhood team.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-fort-wayne-kekiongas-season] The Fort Wayne Kekiongas played their first and only season in 1871 as a charter member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-fort-wayne-kekiongas-season] They finished seventh in the league with a record of 7−12.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-fort-wayne-kekiongas-season] Bobby Mathews, 5 ft 5 in (1.65 m), 140 lbs, and 20 years old, hurled a 2−0 shutout for the Kekiongas.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-new-york-mutuals-season] The **New York Mutuals** baseball team (1857–1876) joined the National Association for the league's debut season in 1871.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-new-york-mutuals-season] The Mutuals went 16-17 and finished in fifth place.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-new-york-mutuals-season] Pitcher Rynie Wolters led the NA in runs batted in, with 44.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players, the Athletic Baseball Club of Philadelphia was one of the first clubs to join.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Athletics had been around since 1860 as an amateur club.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] Led by their captain and pitcher, Dick McBride, the team went 21–7 and won the first NA title during the 1871 season.
[src:1871-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] Philadelphia's third baseman, Levi Meyerle, led the league with a .492 batting average.
